latestPosts.caption: We recently went to How's Your Oni in Greenpoint. We tried their onigiri and okonomiyaki and my word, they were delicious! If you are looking for an authentic Japanese meal, I highly recommend going!

Took a spontaneous trip to Noordhoek today for a sunset and a visit to @aegirproject - our favorite brewery in Cape Town 😍
What a lovely evening! Definitely a must see in the city!

Anyone else been feeling really tired lately? Did you know there are a few foods that balance blood sugar levels better than others and ensure more energy throughout the day?

Check out the list below for ideas on how to boost energy levels and slide across for some meal ideas🥑

▪️WATER!
If you feel tired, it's often because you are dehydrated. Try get 1-2 liters of water in per day.

▪️Avocados
Rich in B vitamins and good fats. 80% of the carbohydrate content in avo's is fiber which helps to sustain energy.

▪️Oats/Oatmeal
Rich source of complex carbs which ensures sustained energy throughout the day.

▪️Bananas
Fantastic source of complex carbs, vitamin B6 and potassium and one of the best foods for energy.

▪️Yogurt
Rich in lactose and galactose which are simple sugars that provide evergy. 

▪️Cinnamon
Helps to keep blood sugar levels stable which in turn helps to stabilise energy.

▪️Hummus
Chickpeas are a good source of complex carbs and fiber which your body uses to stabilise energy. While the tahini and olive help to slow down the absorption of carbs (keeping blood sugar steady).

▪️Dates
High in natural sugar and great for a quick boast of energy. Pair this this yogurt and banana and you'll have a boost of energy that's prolonged throughout the day. 

▪️Quinoa
Great source of complex carbs which helps to prolong energy throughout the day. 

▪️Eggs
Packed with protein, leucine (an amino acid) , and B vitamins, which help enzymes perform their roles in the process of turning food into energy.

▪️Cashews
 Rich in fiber, healthy fats, and plant protein. They're a strong source of copper, magnesium and manganese which are key ingredients for energy production.

▪️Sweet Potatoes
Fantastic source of iron, magnesium and vitamin C which is needed for energy production.

▪️Lentils
Great source of carbs and fiber. Helps to replenish iron, folate, zinc and manganese which increases energy levels. 

#energymeals #nutrition #goodfood #healthymeals

latestPosts.caption:
Gluten-free granola🥣

If you're keen for a delicious and healthy breakfast option, try our gluten-free granola recipe out! 

Ingredients:
2 cups gluten-free rolled oats
3/4 cup raw nuts (almonds, pecans, or any others you like), chopped 
1/2 tsp salt
1/4 teaspoon cinnamon (you could add a little more if you like a stronger cinnamon flavor)
1/4 cup melted coconut oil
1/4 cup honey 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla essence (optional)

Method:
Pre-heat your oven to 180'C / 350'F.
In a large mixing bowl combine your oats, nuts, salt and cinnamon.
Pour in the coconut oil, honey and vanilla mixing well until everything is coated evenly. 
Place your oat mixute into a lined baking sheet and spread it out evenly. 
Bake until lightly golden - roughly 20 - 25 minutes. Make sure to stir the mixture half way through baking to ensure no large clumps form.
 Allow to cool and enjoy!

latestPosts.caption:
Chocolate & Peanut Butter Bars

These refined sugar free and gluten free bars are so delicious!! Check out the recipe below and let me know what you think when you try it 🙌

Ingredients :
1 cup sugar free peanut butter
1 teaspoon salt
1/2 cup honey
1 cup gluten free oats flour
100g dark chocolate (I used 70% but you can go darker if you like because the base is quite sweet).

Method :
Mix together the peanut butter, salt, honey and oat flour. Once combined, press into a lined baking tray.
Melt the dark chocolate in the microwave at 30 second intervals until melted (you could at 1/2 teaspoon of coconut oil to help it run).
Pour the melted chocolate over the peanut butter mixture. Freeze for at least an hour.
Cut into slices and enjoy!

Blend until smooth 🤗

latestPosts.caption:
Butter Chicken

(For a veg option sub the chicken out for cauliflower and add veg stock instead of chicken stock)

Ingredients:
Marinade:
800g boneless and skinless chicken breasts cut cubes. 
1 cup plain yogurt
3 cloves minced garlic (finely grated with a microplane) 
1 tablespoon minced ginger (finely grated with a microplane) 
2 teaspoons garam masala (or curry powder)
1 teaspoon turmeric
1 teaspoon ground cumin
1/2 teaspoon red chilli powder
1/2 teaspoon of salt

Sauce:
2 tablespoons olive oil
1/2 onion, chopped
3 cloves garlic, minced
1 tablespoon ginger, minced or finely chopped
1 teaspoons ground cumin
1 teaspoons garam masala
1 teaspoon ground coriander
400g crushed tomatoes (fresh or canned) 
1/2 teaspoon chilli powder(adjust to your taste) 
1/2 teaspoons salt (or to taste)
1 cup of heavy or thickened cream (or coconut cream)
1 cup chicken stock (I make mine using a chicken stock cube + 1 cup of water) 
1 tablespoon honey 
1/2 teaspoon fenugreek leaves (optional as they are hard to find!)
Knob of butter (20g)

Method:
In a bowl, combine chicken with all the ingredients for the chicken marinade; let marinate for at minimum 1 hour (or overnight).
Heat oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add chicken pieces in batches, making sure not to overcrowd the pan. Fry until browned, 2-3 mins each side. (They don't need to be cooked through at this stage because they will cook through in the sauce). Season your chicken with salt while frying. 

Fry the onions until brown and soft (about 5-7 mins). 
Add garlic and ginger and sauté for a minute, before adding the ground coriander, cumin and garam masala (or curry powder), sauté for 10 seconds until flavors are released, stirring in between.
Add crushed tomatoes and chili. Let simmer for about 5 minutes, stirring occasionally until sauce thickens.
Remove from heat, place the mixture into a  blender and blend until smooth (adding water as necessary). Place back in the pan with the cream, honey, fenugreek and chicken and cook for 10 minutes or until chicken is cooked through and sauce is thick. Stir in your knob of butter.

Garnish with coriander and serve with basmati rice.

latestPosts.caption:
Refined sugar-free, gluten-free, choc-chip, oatmeal cookies 😍

These cookies don't last 5 mins in our house. As soon as I say they are up for grabs, they are gone! With the weather getting cooler in SA I find myself craving sweet things and the great thing about these cookies is that they are only sweetened with honey! Warm, gooey and layered with dark chocolate pieces, these are an absolute must try!

Ingredients:
1 cup sugar free peanut butter
1 cup honey
2 eggs
2 cup gluten-free oats 
Pinch of salt
1 teaspoon vanilla essense
1/2 teaspoon cinnamon 
100g dark chocolate

Method:
Mix together peanut butter, honey, salt, vanilla essence and cinnamon. Add the eggs one at a time, mixing to combine after each addition. Add the dark chocolate and oats. If the mixture is too runny add a little bit more oats. The dough should still be slightly wet but firm. Place in the fridge for 1-2 hours (the hardest part!). 
Bake at 180'C for 6-8 minutes.
.

latestPosts.caption:
Reduced Orange Juice Spritzer with Rosemary

Today was warm! I wore shorts all day and relished in the fact that the days are warming up for summer. This orange juice spritzer is definitely one that I will be making on repeat this summer! It's super easy to make and so refreshing! Plus it's naturally sweetened, so it's guilt free for all you who are getting those summer bodies ready 😉

Recipe
15-20 oranges /naartjies
1 lemon
1-2 teaspoons honey or maple syrup (optional especially if your oranges are very sweet)
1 large bottle sparkling water

Method
Juice the oranges and lemon and place into a saucepan. Place the pan on medium-high heat and bring to a boil. Once it's at boiling point allow to simmer gently and reduce for 20 minutes. Once it's reduced and slightly thickened allow to cool.
To serve roughly bruise and crush a sprig or two of rosemary and add it to a glass with ice. Pour in a quarter of your orange reduction. Top with sparking water and enjoy!
.
